<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="354" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,258,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1626,1651]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kanmiya, 1971" authorityName="Kanmiya" authorityYear="1971" box="[776,1092,1626,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ischaemi">
<emphasis box="[776,910,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">D. ischaemi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kanmiya, K." box="[917,1092,1626,1651]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="157 - 180" refId="ref12133" refString="Kanmiya, K. (1971) Study on the genus Dicraeus Loew from Japan and Formosa (Diptera, Chloropidae). Mushi, 45, 157 - 180." type="journal article" year="1971">Kanmiya, 1971</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from the latter by the following features: ocellar triangle reaching anterior margin of frons; first flagellomere round dorsodistally; surstylus distinctly shorter than depth of epandrium in lateral view, basal 2/3 nearly parallel-sided, recurved posteriorly; some thickened setae on middle surface; cercus absent. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kanmiya" authorityYear="1971" box="[1051,1185,1734,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ischaemi">
<emphasis box="[1051,1185,1734,1758]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">D. ischaemi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ocellar triangle is extended to a little beyond middle of frons; the first flagellomere has a dorsodistal angle; the surstylus is slender, slightly concave at middle, broadly round apically, and has 5 long thick setae; and the cercus is slender, finger-like (
<bibRefCitation author="Kanmiya, K." box="[158,330,1842,1867]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="157 - 180" refId="ref12133" refString="Kanmiya, K. (1971) Study on the genus Dicraeus Loew from Japan and Formosa (Diptera, Chloropidae). Mushi, 45, 157 - 180." type="journal article" year="1971">Kanmiya 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="354" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,258,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1878,1903]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Yang &amp; Nartshuk" authorityYear="2019" box="[744,882,1879,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassispinus">
<emphasis box="[744,882,1879,1902]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">crassispinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(“crassispina”), referring to the thickened setulae on inner side of surstylus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
